      question: "How much does it cost to replace a water heater in Tucson, and can I get a tankless one installed in the same spot?",
      answer: "Water heater replacement in Tucson typically costs $1,200-$2,500 for standard tank models (40-50 gallon gas or electric) and $2,500-$4,500 for tankless installations. Tankless units can usually be installed in the same location as your old tank water heater, though there are important considerations for Tucson homes. Gas tankless units require larger gas lines (often ¾-inch instead of ½-inch), proper venting (either PVC or stainless steel), and adequate combustion air—modifications that add $500-$1,200 to installation costs. Electric tankless systems may need electrical panel upgrades (200-amp service) costing $800-$2,000 additional. That said, tankless water heaters are excellent for Tucson's hard water when properly maintained with biannual descaling service. They provide endless hot water, last 20+ years versus 8-12 for tanks, and save 30-40% on water heating costs. We install Rinnai, Navien, Rheem, and Noritz tankless systems optimized for our 16-18 grain hard water. Most installations complete in 4-6 hours. We also offer hybrid heat pump water heaters ($1,800-$3,200 installed) that work exceptionally well in Tucson's hot garages and save 60% on energy costs. Call (520) 333-2665 for a free in-home assessment with exact pricing and energy savings calculations specific to your home."
